To solve the problem, we start by noting that a regular hexagon can be divided into six equilateral triangles. Each of these triangles has a perimeter of 21 inches. 

First, we find the side length of each equilateral triangle. Since the perimeter is 21 inches, each side of the triangle is:
\[
\frac{21}{3} = 7 \text{ inches}
\]

The side length of each equilateral triangle is equal to the side length of the regular hexagon. Therefore, each side of the hexagon is also 7 inches.

A regular hexagon has six sides, so its perimeter is:
\[
6 \times 7 = 42 \text{ inches}
\]

Thus, the perimeter of the regular hexagon is \(\boxed{42}\) inches.
