A regular hexagon can be divided into six equilateral triangles. Each of these triangles has a perimeter of 21 inches. 

First, we find the length of each side of the equilateral triangle:
\[
\text{Perimeter of the triangle} = 21 \text{ inches}
\]
\[
\text{Length of each side of the triangle} = \frac{21}{3} = 7 \text{ inches}
\]

Since each side of the equilateral triangle is equal to the side length of the regular hexagon, each side of the hexagon is 7 inches. 

Next, we calculate the perimeter of the regular hexagon, which has six sides:
\[
\text{Perimeter of the hexagon} = 6 \times 7 = 42 \text{ inches}
\]

Thus, the perimeter of the regular hexagon is \boxed{42} inches.
